<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">In my book =E2=80=
=9CThe Next 100 Years,=E2=80=9D published in 2009, I predicted that in the =
2020s the United States would experience a massive socio-economic crisis, a=
s well as a substantial institutional crisis. The forecast was based on his=
toric cycles, whereby the former occurs roughly every 50 years and the latt=
er roughly every 80 years. Socio-economic crises wrecked the U.S. in the 19=
70s, the 1920s, the late 1800s, and so on back to the founding. Likewise, t=
he country underwent institutional reformation after the Civil War and then=
 again after World War II, 80 years apart. I had (and have) no explanation =
for the regularity. And the realization came not from great intelligence bu=
t from simply observing the obvious.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">In my next book, =
=E2=80=9CThe Storm Before the Calm,=E2=80=9D published in 2020, I forecast =
that the socio-economic crisis would begin to emerge at the beginning of th=
e decade, and that the full storm would begin with the 2024 election. With =
both cycles peaking together, my prediction was that the storm would be mor=
e intense than usual but that the country would survive and, afterward, flo=
urish. So it was after the prior crises. I did not (and do not) think presi=
dents create these crises, but I do think that the crises create presidents=
 who attack existing institutions and then, if reelected, create new ones. =
In the current case, President Donald Trump can only serve out the remainer=
 of his term. Therefore, a new president will preside over the two crises, =
with the storm calming toward the end of the decade.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">=E2=80=9CThe Storm=
 Before the Calm=E2=80=9D also noted that the two institutions in crisis wo=
uld be the federal government and universities. The federal government that=
 had emerged from World War II was based on expertise. It was the experts, =
after all, that created the technologies and strategies of the Second World=
 War. The problem with what might be called the technocratic state is that =
the experts had massive power but, being experts, little oversight of or co=
llaboration with bureaucratic structures. The old structure, in which the p=
resident governed with generalist advisers who helped manage and coordinate=
 the system, was turned into a system of focused expertise, powerful in its=
 domain but uncoordinated with other expert domains. In effect, the federal=
 government=E2=80=99s bureaucracy governed the nation, sometimes contradict=
orily. I argued that the institutional crisis of the 2020s, like previous i=
nstitutional crises, would be painful because it would overturn norms, gene=
rate division and leave blood on the floor, figuratively and literally. Suc=
h was the case in previous crises during the Revolutionary War, the Civil W=
ar and World War II.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">=E2=80=9CThe Storm=
 Before the Calm=E2=80=9D also predicted that another institution =E2=80=93=
 the university =E2=80=93 would be reformed and reorganized. It was simply =
a matter of economic necessity. Government college loans had exceeded the a=
mount of debt in the subprime mortgage crisis, and universities had no inte=
rest in controlling tuition costs. University systems were also developing =
an ideological concept as a principle of education and functioning: diversi=
ty. Universities have always had ideological and social principles, but as =
the social order shifted, it clashed with university ideology. The same thi=
ng had happened at elite universities in the first half of the 20th century=
 when they started to base admission on social class standing. This system =
was destroyed by the GI Bill, flooding universities with war veterans from =
the lower classes. Schools adopted egalitarianism as a governing principle =
of both admission and internal ideology. Just as elitist universities had b=
een overwhelmed by veterans, universities were following the bill's extreme=
 application, this time focused on racial equality, gender equality, and th=
en various other sexual identities, with bureaucracies ensuring outcomes.</=
p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Universities are i=
